oved social services, land reform, expanding electoral participation, and racial integration.In Brazil, Seidman takes us from the shopfloor, where disenfranchized workers organized for better wages and working conditions, to the strikes and protests that spread to local communities. Similar demands for radical change emerged in South Africa, where community groups in black townships joined organized labor in a challenge to minority rule that linked class consciousness to racial oppression. Seidman details the complex dynamics of these militant movements and develops a broad analysis of how newly industrializing countries shape the opportunities for labor to express demands. Her work will be welcomed by those interested in labor studies, social theory, and the politics of newly industrializing regions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLabor movementxHistoryx20th centuryxBrazil. 0aLabor movementxHistoryx20th centuryxSouth Africa. 0aLabor movementzBrazilxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor movementzSouth AfricaxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor unionsxHistoryx20th centuryxBrazil. 0aLabor unionsxHistoryx20th centuryxSouth AfricaxBrazilxSouth Africa. 0aLabor unionszBrazilxHistoryy20th century. 0aLabor unionszSouth AfricaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / General.2bisacsh  aauthoritarian state.  abetter wages.  ablack townships.  abrazil.  abusiness and the state.  aclass consciousness.  adevelopment.  adisenfranchised workers.  aeconomic growth.  aelectoral politics.  aindustrialization.  ainequality.  alabor movements.  alabor studies.  alabor.  aland reform.  aorganized labor.  apolitical repression.  apolitics.  aprotests.  arace relations.  aracial integration.  arapid industrialization.  ashopfloor.  asocial repression.  